You have all these
Googles and everything--

00:11:35.790 --> 00:11:38.400
didn't change the life
of Bandladeshi people.

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:39.750
So one idea came to my mind.

00:11:39.750 --> 00:11:41.610
Why don't we bring solar energy?

00:11:41.610 --> 00:11:43.320
Everybody said, no,
this is difficult.

00:11:43.320 --> 00:11:44.900
You can't do it in Bangladesh.

00:11:44.900 --> 00:11:46.860
It's very expensive technology.

00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:49.840
So I started looking at it, how
expensive it is, cn it be done.

00:11:49.840 --> 00:11:51.810
So finally, I decided
we'll do that.

00:11:51.810 --> 00:11:53.230
We created a company right away.

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:55.300
We called it Grameen
Energy, or Grameen Shakti,

00:11:55.300 --> 00:11:58.800
in Bengali, to sell
solar home system.

00:11:58.800 --> 00:12:00.930
Initially, it was so
difficult to convince people.

00:12:00.930 --> 00:12:01.680
They said, no, no.

00:12:01.680 --> 00:12:02.950
This is too expensive.

00:12:02.950 --> 00:12:04.020
We are not used to it.

00:12:04.020 --> 00:12:05.270
Maybe it's just a magic.

00:12:05.270 --> 00:12:07.100
It will disappear after a while.

00:12:07.100 --> 00:12:09.310
It's not a guaranteed thing.

00:12:09.310 --> 00:12:13.290
So then we learn how to address
this issue with the people.

00:12:13.290 --> 00:12:16.357
We ask them how much money you
spend on kerosene every month.

00:12:16.357 --> 00:12:17.190
Then they calculate.

00:12:17.190 --> 00:12:18.950
Ah, we spend so much.

00:12:18.950 --> 00:12:21.709
And our deal is you give me
the kerosene money every month,

00:12:21.709 --> 00:12:22.500
whatever was spent.

00:12:22.500 --> 00:12:24.112
I give you the electricity.

00:12:24.112 --> 00:12:26.570
And you continue to pay the
same amount over the next three

00:12:26.570 --> 00:12:27.730
years.

00:12:27.730 --> 00:12:29.910
And then after the
three years, you

00:12:29.910 --> 00:12:32.425
don't have to pay a penny
to anybody anywhere.

00:12:32.425 --> 00:12:34.050
So you also don't
have to buy kerosene.

00:12:34.050 --> 00:12:35.490
You don't have to pay anybody.

00:12:35.490 --> 00:12:38.010
So then this is
attractive proposition.

00:12:38.010 --> 00:12:39.260
Then it started soaring.

00:12:39.260 --> 00:12:42.540
We started selling thousands and
thousands of solar home system.

00:12:42.540 --> 00:12:47.160
Today, we have 1.8 million
solar home in Bangladesh.

00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:52.500
In the middle of it, we became
the largest off-grid energy

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:54.822
system in the whole world
because there isn't any more.

00:12:54.822 --> 00:12:56.280
JACK HIDARY: Also
you're empowering

00:12:56.280 --> 00:13:00.360
all those entrepreneurs who
are selling the Shakti system.

00:13:00.360 --> 00:13:02.880
And that brings us really to
the second two zeros, right?

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:05.980
So we have first zero in
terms of climate change.

00:13:05.980 --> 00:13:07.920
And then in terms
of carbon emissions,

00:13:07.920 --> 00:13:09.884
we want to have net
zero in terms of that,

00:13:09.884 --> 00:13:11.800
and then in terms of
unemployment and poverty.

00:13:11.800 --> 00:13:13.770
So many of your
businesses are not just

00:13:13.770 --> 00:13:17.070
delivering interesting services
to people, such as solar power.

00:13:17.070 --> 00:13:18.450
We also can look
at Grameenphone,

00:13:18.450 --> 00:13:19.324
which is [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:19.324 --> 00:13:22.410
But also empowers
thousands to millions

00:13:22.410 --> 00:13:24.810
of entrepreneurs who
take control of that

00:13:24.810 --> 00:13:25.820
and then deliver that.

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:26.920
And Grameenphone is an example.

00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:28.670
So maybe talk about
these next two zeros--

00:13:28.670 --> 00:13:30.300
zero unemployment
and zero poverty.

00:13:30.300 --> 00:13:32.610
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: On the zero
poverty, one of the things

00:13:32.610 --> 00:13:35.330
we did, the microcredit,
to help people to start

00:13:35.330 --> 00:13:37.080
income generation for them.

00:13:37.080 --> 00:13:40.140
And focusing on women because
they are the unused resource,

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:43.680
and people never thought
that women can contribute

00:13:43.680 --> 00:13:44.680
in income of the family.

00:13:44.680 --> 00:13:45.900
We just focused on them.

00:13:45.900 --> 00:13:46.690
JACK HIDARY: What's
your statistics,

00:13:46.690 --> 00:13:49.023
by the way, in terms of how
many people in the community

00:13:49.023 --> 00:13:51.160
are affected when you
help start one business,

00:13:51.160 --> 00:13:52.620
one microfinance business?

00:13:52.620 --> 00:13:53.970
What's been your stats on that?

00:13:53.970 --> 00:13:57.000
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: We don't have
stat in that research terms.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.480
But you start buying things.

00:13:59.480 --> 00:14:00.550
Somebody sells more.

00:14:00.550 --> 00:14:03.390
So you start selling
things, somebody starts--

00:14:03.390 --> 00:14:05.805
JACK HIDARY: I've seen a
stat of about 50 to one,

00:14:05.805 --> 00:14:07.860
that for every
one woman that you

00:14:07.860 --> 00:14:10.830
help with a
microfinance-oriented

00:14:10.830 --> 00:14:13.410
entrepreneurship, about
50 people are directly

00:14:13.410 --> 00:14:14.999
affected in terms of that.

00:14:14.999 --> 00:14:16.290
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: So we did that.

00:14:16.290 --> 00:14:21.940
And we said the poverty is not
created by the poor people.

00:14:21.940 --> 00:14:24.150
Poverty is created by
the system that we built.

00:14:24.150 --> 00:14:26.460
That's the reason how
they're poor because it

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:28.040
is imposed from outside.

00:14:28.040 --> 00:14:30.150
It is not grown from inside.

00:14:30.150 --> 00:14:31.990
So we are trying
to fix that system.

00:14:31.990 --> 00:14:34.560
One of the things
which came to us

00:14:34.560 --> 00:14:37.170
quickly is the
financial system, how

00:14:37.170 --> 00:14:41.100
to amend the financial system,
design the financial system

00:14:41.100 --> 00:14:43.200
to work for the poor people.

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:46.020
They were explaining to us,
the bankers and so on, no,

00:14:46.020 --> 00:14:49.510
it cannot be done because
poor are not creditworthy.

00:14:49.510 --> 00:14:51.710
So I kept asking them,
should you tell poor

00:14:51.710 --> 00:14:54.439
if they are creditworthy or
not, or whether poor people,

00:14:54.439 --> 00:14:56.480
or the people in [INAUDIBLE]
tell you whether you

00:14:56.480 --> 00:14:58.170
are people-worthy or not.

00:14:58.170 --> 00:14:59.979
So you have to be people-worthy.

00:14:59.979 --> 00:15:01.020
So that's your challenge.

00:15:01.020 --> 00:15:02.220
You have to come up with that.

00:15:02.220 --> 00:15:03.636
But they didn't
take it seriously.

00:15:03.636 --> 00:15:07.520
We took our job seriously to
make it a people-worthy system.

00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:09.060
And we created that system.

00:15:09.060 --> 00:15:11.630
And it works not only
in Bangladesh, globally.

00:15:11.630 --> 00:15:14.070
Today, Grameen Bank,
within Bangladesh,

00:15:14.070 --> 00:15:16.050
has over 9 million borrowers.

00:15:16.050 --> 00:15:18.900
97% of them are women.

00:15:18.900 --> 00:15:20.380
And they own the bank.

00:15:20.380 --> 00:15:22.900
And the city and the board,
making decisions for the bank

00:15:22.900 --> 00:15:24.190
and so on.

00:15:24.190 --> 00:15:27.820
Largest bank in the country
in terms of clientele.

00:15:27.820 --> 00:15:29.770
And it's very
well-run in the sense

00:15:29.770 --> 00:15:32.830
that it is sustainable,
never lost money.

00:15:32.830 --> 00:15:33.730
Surpluses come.

00:15:33.730 --> 00:15:34.390
Profits come.

00:15:34.390 --> 00:15:35.669
Profit is distributed.

00:15:35.669 --> 00:15:37.710
JACK HIDARY: Having
borrowers on the board itself

00:15:37.710 --> 00:15:39.100
is an unusual move for a bank.

00:15:39.100 --> 00:15:41.597
Let's just put it that way.

00:15:41.597 --> 00:15:43.180
MUHAMMAD YUNUS:
Because they own this.

00:15:43.180 --> 00:15:45.190
This is their bank.

00:15:45.190 --> 00:15:46.930
And they run it
for their benefit.

00:15:46.930 --> 00:15:50.230
So we wanted to see this
is an institution which

00:15:50.230 --> 00:15:54.040
is designed for the purpose
of helping people come out

00:15:54.040 --> 00:15:54.920
of poverty.

00:15:54.920 --> 00:15:57.670
So that's one that
we try to make income

00:15:57.670 --> 00:15:59.950
generation, poverty, and so on.

00:15:59.950 --> 00:16:02.860
And one issue come that they
are all illiterate women, all

00:16:02.860 --> 00:16:05.440
these 9 million
families that we have.

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:08.620
We wanted to make sure the
children from those families

00:16:08.620 --> 00:16:10.480
do not remain illiterate.

00:16:10.480 --> 00:16:13.030
So we wanted to make sure
the children go to school,

00:16:13.030 --> 00:16:13.780
have education.

00:16:13.780 --> 00:16:15.420
Grameen Bank took
the responsibility

00:16:15.420 --> 00:16:18.850
of ensuring children stay
in school, don't drop out,

00:16:18.850 --> 00:16:23.060
and give scholarship, give
loan for higher education.

00:16:23.060 --> 00:16:24.840
But one thing came out of it.

00:16:24.840 --> 00:16:26.840
After they come out of
graduation, after that

00:16:26.840 --> 00:16:28.270
there's no job in Bangladesh.

00:16:28.270 --> 00:16:32.450
With 165 million, you're not
creating those kind of jobs.

00:16:32.450 --> 00:16:35.020
And I couldn't give
any solution to that.

00:16:35.020 --> 00:16:37.270
Then I took a
different position.

00:16:37.270 --> 00:16:38.730
I challenged the young people.

00:16:38.730 --> 00:16:40.630
I said, why are you
looking for job?

00:16:40.630 --> 00:16:41.875
Who told you to have a job?

00:16:41.875 --> 00:16:44.350
I said, a job is a
completely wrong idea.

00:16:44.350 --> 00:16:47.290
I said, it is just pushing
you in the completely wrong

00:16:47.290 --> 00:16:48.370
direction.

00:16:48.370 --> 00:16:51.910
You should feel like you
are not a job seeker.

00:16:51.910 --> 00:16:53.360
You are a job creator.

00:16:53.360 --> 00:16:54.510
Feel like a job creator.

00:16:54.510 --> 00:16:55.500
Act like a job creator.

00:16:55.500 --> 00:16:57.070
Feel big rather than feel small.

00:16:57.070 --> 00:16:57.850
JACK HIDARY: And
then you started

00:16:57.850 --> 00:16:59.810
an organization called
[? Nobin, ?] which--

00:16:59.810 --> 00:17:01.840
talk about that in
terms of that goes

00:17:01.840 --> 00:17:04.630
now outside of just
microfinance and banking

00:17:04.630 --> 00:17:05.847
into entrepreneurship.

00:17:05.847 --> 00:17:08.180
And again, your message to
millennials around the world,

00:17:08.180 --> 00:17:10.660
not as Bangladesh,
is instead of just

00:17:10.660 --> 00:17:12.276
thinking about
taking a job, think

00:17:12.276 --> 00:17:13.359
about starting a business.

00:17:13.359 --> 00:17:15.650
Obviously here in Silicon
Valley, a lot of young people

00:17:15.650 --> 00:17:17.450
do take that advice.

00:17:17.450 --> 00:17:19.765
But you really see that
as a global message.

00:17:19.765 --> 00:17:20.890
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: Absolutely.

00:17:20.890 --> 00:17:24.490
So we tell them,
look, your mother

00:17:24.490 --> 00:17:28.569
took a loan 20 years
back, 35 years back--

00:17:28.569 --> 00:17:30.670
$20, $30, $50.

00:17:30.670 --> 00:17:32.890
That's how her life
began with that.

00:17:32.890 --> 00:17:35.230
And she became an entrepreneur.

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:38.890
If your illiterate
mother, who never crossed

00:17:38.890 --> 00:17:41.500
the boundaries of
your village, could

00:17:41.500 --> 00:17:44.910
turn into an entrepreneur
with a $40 loan,

00:17:44.910 --> 00:17:47.410
what's wrong with you with all
the education and everything

00:17:47.410 --> 00:17:48.490
that you have learned?

00:17:48.490 --> 00:17:51.760
You are looking for somebody
to help you to get a good job.

00:17:51.760 --> 00:17:53.620
This is not fair.

00:17:53.620 --> 00:17:55.780
You should be thinking
about doing better than what

00:17:55.780 --> 00:17:56.650
your mother has done--

00:17:56.650 --> 00:17:57.155
JACK HIDARY: Job creation.

00:17:57.155 --> 00:17:58.940
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: Job creation.

00:17:58.940 --> 00:18:00.035
You have regressed.

00:18:00.035 --> 00:18:01.270
JACK HIDARY: So how
does the system work?

00:18:01.270 --> 00:18:01.750
How does it know--

00:18:01.750 --> 00:18:03.166
MUHAMMAD YUNUS:
So what we did, we

00:18:03.166 --> 00:18:06.340
created a social business
fund, a venture capital fund,

00:18:06.340 --> 00:18:09.580
and asked all the young people
to come up with business ideas.

00:18:09.580 --> 00:18:12.555
If they don't have business
ideas, we go and you say,

00:18:12.555 --> 00:18:13.850
go and consult your mother.

00:18:13.850 --> 00:18:15.650
She has lots of business ideas.

00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:17.650
So why don't you should
come up with one of them

00:18:17.650 --> 00:18:19.233
and explain to us
what you want to do.

00:18:19.233 --> 00:18:22.990
Then we invest in your business
as a partner, not as a lender.

00:18:22.990 --> 00:18:25.000
So we become a
partner with you--

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:26.770
it's our business
and your business--

00:18:26.770 --> 00:18:28.321
and make it successful.

00:18:28.321 --> 00:18:30.070
And once it's successful,
return the money

00:18:30.070 --> 00:18:31.900
that we gave you because
we are a social business.

00:18:31.900 --> 00:18:33.600
We are not interested
in your profit.

00:18:33.600 --> 00:18:34.940
Profit just stays with you.

00:18:34.940 --> 00:18:35.440
And go on.

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:36.760
We just put you in the orbit.

00:18:36.760 --> 00:18:38.010
You go on.

00:18:38.010 --> 00:18:40.320
Be entrepreneur like your
mother, and be proud--

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:43.210
JACK HIDARY: So tell
us about the process.

00:18:43.210 --> 00:18:45.302
When they apply as an
entrepreneur, what happens?

00:18:45.302 --> 00:18:46.510
How do you evaluate all this?

00:18:46.510 --> 00:18:48.070
MUHAMMAD YUNUS:
The basic principle

00:18:48.070 --> 00:18:51.460
of what we apply is
nobody is rejected.

00:18:51.460 --> 00:18:54.860
So anybody can apply, and
it will not be rejected.

00:18:54.860 --> 00:18:58.564
And nobody's abandoned,
meaning that even if you fail,

00:18:58.564 --> 00:18:59.730
still we'll not abandon you.

00:18:59.730 --> 00:19:03.860
We'll take you back to and start
helping you to do it again.

00:19:03.860 --> 00:19:07.150
But no, this action means you
come up with the basic idea,

00:19:07.150 --> 00:19:09.194
but it's not formulated
in a elaborate manner

00:19:09.194 --> 00:19:10.610
that you have not
thought through.

00:19:10.610 --> 00:19:12.880
So we'll help you
develop it in a--

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:16.150
go to the full extent and
make it a complete one.

00:19:16.150 --> 00:19:17.450
And then we invest in it.

00:19:17.450 --> 00:19:19.957
So we work together rather
than say, ah, your project is--

00:19:19.957 --> 00:19:22.040
JACK HIDARY: So it's not
just the money obviously.

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:23.831
And what we learned
here in Silicon Valley,

00:19:23.831 --> 00:19:25.900
obviously, is that looking
at Y Combinator and so

00:19:25.900 --> 00:19:29.144
many incubators, you can't
just give someone a check

00:19:29.144 --> 00:19:30.310
and invest in their company.

00:19:30.310 --> 00:19:32.018
You've got to really
nurture that company

00:19:32.018 --> 00:19:34.060
and help them along and
help shape that company.

00:19:34.060 --> 00:19:34.780
And that's what you're finding.

00:19:34.780 --> 00:19:35.510
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: That's right.

00:19:35.510 --> 00:19:36.220
So we do that.

00:19:36.220 --> 00:19:40.480
Only difference between the
venture capital and Silicon

00:19:40.480 --> 00:19:42.910
Valley, perhaps, would be
that you want to profit

00:19:42.910 --> 00:19:45.220
from the ventures itself.

00:19:45.220 --> 00:19:46.522
We took the profit part out.

00:19:46.522 --> 00:19:47.480
We are not interested--

00:19:47.480 --> 00:19:48.580
JACK HIDARY: Social
business fund.

00:19:48.580 --> 00:19:49.420
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: It's
a social business.

00:19:49.420 --> 00:19:50.770
So you do that.

00:19:50.770 --> 00:19:53.680
That's [INAUDIBLE] people like,
OK, if I can take the money,

00:19:53.680 --> 00:19:54.370
I can do that.

00:19:54.370 --> 00:19:55.831
And all the profit
belongs to me.

00:19:55.831 --> 00:19:56.330
Why not?

00:19:56.330 --> 00:19:57.788
JACK HIDARY: And
now professor, you

00:19:57.788 --> 00:20:00.460
are scaling because, I think,
you gave a talk in India

00:20:00.460 --> 00:20:01.740
about seven years ago.

00:20:01.740 --> 00:20:03.281
And one of the people
in the audience

00:20:03.281 --> 00:20:05.200
came up to you after
the talk and said, hey,

00:20:05.200 --> 00:20:07.690
I'm interested in starting
a social business fund to do

00:20:07.690 --> 00:20:09.180
this exact same thing in India.

00:20:09.180 --> 00:20:10.300
And you said, well, maybe he is.

00:20:10.300 --> 00:20:10.925
Maybe he isn't.

00:20:10.925 --> 00:20:11.470
Who knows?

00:20:11.470 --> 00:20:13.150
A few months later,
you get a letter,

00:20:13.150 --> 00:20:15.070
saying that he's
ready with $1 million.

00:20:15.070 --> 00:20:17.110
And you gave the OK
for that to happen.

00:20:17.110 --> 00:20:19.280
And now seven years later,
they're still going.

00:20:19.280 --> 00:20:20.380
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: They're
still doing very well.

00:20:20.380 --> 00:20:21.670
JACK HIDARY: So
what happened there?

00:20:21.670 --> 00:20:22.670
Who was that individual?

00:20:22.670 --> 00:20:24.390
MUHAMMAD YUNUS:
[INAUDIBLE] from Bombay.

00:20:24.390 --> 00:20:26.014
[INAUDIBLE] just
speaking [INAUDIBLE]..

00:20:26.014 --> 00:20:28.590
Then he comes out
of the lecture hall.

00:20:28.590 --> 00:20:32.110
He said, I like your
idea about this.

00:20:32.110 --> 00:20:32.740
Can I do that?

00:20:32.740 --> 00:20:33.970
I said, of course you can do it.

00:20:33.970 --> 00:20:35.261
But I didn't take it seriously.

00:20:35.261 --> 00:20:37.480
People say that all the
time, that I want to do it.

00:20:37.480 --> 00:20:39.010
But I don't know what happened.

00:20:39.010 --> 00:20:41.020
But this guy became
very serious.

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:42.280
And then he wrote me a letter.

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:43.480
He said, I want to do that.

00:20:43.480 --> 00:20:47.950
I want to use $1
million of my own money.

00:20:47.950 --> 00:20:50.440
You said, $1 million at
the beginning is enough.

00:20:50.440 --> 00:20:52.000
I said, yes, I
still believe that.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:53.350
Now his answer is beautiful.

00:20:53.350 --> 00:20:55.580
JACK HIDARY: Because it recycles
the money and then it grows.

00:20:55.580 --> 00:20:57.130
We might have some people in
this audience, who will tell

00:20:57.130 --> 00:20:58.670
you after this talk, so yeah.

00:20:58.670 --> 00:21:00.370
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: And that'll
encourage another person

00:21:00.370 --> 00:21:01.530
