And that's, I think,
doing quite well.

00:21:45.890 --> 00:21:46.150
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: Very well.

00:21:46.150 --> 00:21:46.810
JACK HIDARY: Maybe talk about--

00:21:46.810 --> 00:21:48.370
MUHAMMAD YUNUS:
Yeah, it's in Uganda.

00:21:48.370 --> 00:21:51.040
That inspired us, seeing
that they're doing.

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:53.200
So now we look at the
plastic as a major issue.

00:21:53.200 --> 00:21:55.660
And then we're holding a
big conference in plastic

00:21:55.660 --> 00:21:58.560
how to save us
ourselves from plastic

00:21:58.560 --> 00:22:02.030
because the plastic ocean
and all that's happening.

00:22:02.030 --> 00:22:05.200
So how to take
this waste plastic

00:22:05.200 --> 00:22:09.340
and gather and recycle
them in making it

00:22:09.340 --> 00:22:13.490
long-lasting products, like
furniture, like utensils,

00:22:13.490 --> 00:22:15.970
and people can use,
so that they do not

00:22:15.970 --> 00:22:19.940
end up clogging the rivers,
clogging the oceans, and so

00:22:19.940 --> 00:22:20.890
on and so forth.

00:22:20.890 --> 00:22:23.565
And then it's a difficulty
of plastic waste

00:22:23.565 --> 00:22:26.790
is it's now coming to
our food chain, to fish.

00:22:26.790 --> 00:22:29.600
Fish eating them and
kind of digest it,

00:22:29.600 --> 00:22:30.850
sitting in the stomach.

00:22:30.850 --> 00:22:32.010
And we're catching them.

00:22:32.010 --> 00:22:33.190
And it passes on to us.

00:22:33.190 --> 00:22:35.710
And even our water
system in many cities

00:22:35.710 --> 00:22:40.090
have very fine fibers of plastic
coming in to many cities now.

00:22:40.090 --> 00:22:43.060
So it's dangerous
signals already.

00:22:43.060 --> 00:22:45.790
So one of the things
that we are doing,

00:22:45.790 --> 00:22:49.180
as an example learning
from what we did in Uganda,

00:22:49.180 --> 00:22:51.070
take Mekong River in Vietnam.

00:22:51.070 --> 00:22:53.290
It's also filled up
with lots of plastic.

00:22:53.290 --> 00:22:57.282
So set up social businesses
alongside the bank.

00:22:57.282 --> 00:22:58.004
Create--

00:22:58.004 --> 00:22:59.170
JACK HIDARY: Down the river.

00:22:59.170 --> 00:23:00.461
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: Down the river.

00:23:00.461 --> 00:23:03.580
So collect it, and offer people
if you bring this, we pay you.

00:23:03.580 --> 00:23:05.450
So we don't have to
employ lots of people.

00:23:05.450 --> 00:23:06.320
Just you bring it.

00:23:06.320 --> 00:23:10.776
[INAUDIBLE] we buy it from
you, all the waste material.

00:23:10.776 --> 00:23:12.150
You can bring it
from your homes.

00:23:12.150 --> 00:23:13.870
You can bring it
from the rivers.

00:23:13.870 --> 00:23:18.670
So we keep on giving a
recycle and make furniture,

00:23:18.670 --> 00:23:21.190
housing materials so that
people can use it as a housing

00:23:21.190 --> 00:23:22.149
material, and so on.

00:23:22.149 --> 00:23:24.190
So this is something that
we are going to launch.

00:23:24.190 --> 00:23:27.610
And [INAUDIBLE] everybody
else, beware of plastic

00:23:27.610 --> 00:23:30.660
what you do, particularly
in the packaging materials,

00:23:30.660 --> 00:23:32.380
particularly in
the water bottles,

00:23:32.380 --> 00:23:34.210
in the straws, which
are the dangerous part

00:23:34.210 --> 00:23:36.160
of the plastic thing.

00:23:36.160 --> 00:23:38.150
So we see it's possible.

00:23:38.150 --> 00:23:41.050
If you keep your mind
in a creative way

00:23:41.050 --> 00:23:44.860
to address this issue, at the
same time asking the producers

00:23:44.860 --> 00:23:46.940
and the users, be careful.

00:23:46.940 --> 00:23:47.890
Don't use it.

00:23:47.890 --> 00:23:48.820
Use something else.

00:23:48.820 --> 00:23:53.440
Or asking the chemists to come
up with biodegradable plastics

00:23:53.440 --> 00:23:55.454
rather than the one
which is nondegradable.

00:23:55.454 --> 00:23:56.370
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: Great.

00:23:56.370 --> 00:23:58.280
