00:51:34.810 --> 00:51:35.310
Go ahead.

00:51:35.310 --> 00:51:36.600
Make money as long as you can.

00:51:36.600 --> 00:51:38.520
But we are coming to
make it cheaper, better

00:51:38.520 --> 00:51:40.990
for people who are
not rich by you.

00:51:40.990 --> 00:51:41.490
That's all.

00:51:41.490 --> 00:51:43.115
JACK HIDARY: Professor,
here in the US,

00:51:43.115 --> 00:51:46.200
we've seen the rise of the B
corp movement, which is exactly

00:51:46.200 --> 00:51:48.280
the end to this point.

00:51:48.280 --> 00:51:51.450
Because when you start a C
corp or a traditional LLC,

00:51:51.450 --> 00:51:54.960
there's certain responsibilities
you have to your investors.

00:51:54.960 --> 00:51:57.720
And there is this expectation
of dividends going out

00:51:57.720 --> 00:52:00.090
of the company on
a typical basis.

00:52:00.090 --> 00:52:03.780
The B corp allows for more of
a social business structure.

00:52:03.780 --> 00:52:05.460
Started in Vermont
initially, but now

00:52:05.460 --> 00:52:08.482
has spread to a good number
of states across the US

00:52:08.482 --> 00:52:10.440
because companies are
incorporated at the state

00:52:10.440 --> 00:52:12.180
level, not at the federal level.

00:52:12.180 --> 00:52:14.040
And we're seeing a
lot of good traction

00:52:14.040 --> 00:52:15.540
with the B corp
model, which is one

00:52:15.540 --> 00:52:17.970
of the primary social
business models out there.

00:52:17.970 --> 00:52:20.250
So I think we're seeing
some good initial traction.

00:52:20.250 --> 00:52:24.600
And it does help to smooth
out some legal difficulties

00:52:24.600 --> 00:52:27.085
that if you try the C
corp social business,

00:52:27.085 --> 00:52:28.210
you might have some issues.

00:52:28.210 --> 00:52:30.187
So some good signs, I would say.

00:52:30.187 --> 00:52:31.020
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:52:31.020 --> 00:52:32.103
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: Thank you.

00:52:32.103 --> 00:52:33.562
JACK HIDARY: Next
question, please.

00:52:33.562 --> 00:52:34.936
We are just moving
through these.

00:52:34.936 --> 00:52:35.510
This is good.

00:52:35.510 --> 00:52:36.176
Good, professor.

00:52:36.176 --> 00:52:38.530
AUDIENCE: Going back to giving
out loans to women only,

00:52:38.530 --> 00:52:42.100
I was curious if it's because
you try the same model with men

00:52:42.100 --> 00:52:44.590
first and you weren't
getting the money back.

00:52:44.590 --> 00:52:47.410
Or where was this decision
in the trial and error?

00:52:47.410 --> 00:52:52.290
And then also subquestion
is of these businesses

00:52:52.290 --> 00:52:54.790
that these female entrepreneurs
started either in Bangladesh

00:52:54.790 --> 00:52:56.665
or around the world,
was there a common trend

00:52:56.665 --> 00:52:58.500
in the businesses
that they started

00:52:58.500 --> 00:53:00.700
or the ones that
were successful?

00:53:00.700 --> 00:53:02.590
What types of businesses
were successful?

00:53:02.590 --> 00:53:04.340
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: On
the men-women issue,

00:53:04.340 --> 00:53:07.300
that we started this
in Grameen Bank when

00:53:07.300 --> 00:53:12.100
we just a little initiative
in one village in Jobra,

00:53:12.100 --> 00:53:15.970
which is just next to
the university campus.

00:53:15.970 --> 00:53:18.070
I have been criticizing
the bankers a lot.

00:53:18.070 --> 00:53:20.920
I was very nasty towards
the bankers in Bangladesh,

00:53:20.920 --> 00:53:22.630
criticizing them that are wrong.

00:53:22.630 --> 00:53:24.230
Their design is wrong.

00:53:24.230 --> 00:53:25.780
They created an
institution which

00:53:25.780 --> 00:53:27.910
doesn't make any
sense because banks

00:53:27.910 --> 00:53:29.380
are supposed to lend money.

00:53:29.380 --> 00:53:31.030
They do it in such a funny way.

00:53:31.030 --> 00:53:33.482
They lend money to people who
already have lots of money.

00:53:33.482 --> 00:53:35.690
They don't lend money to
people who don't have money.

00:53:35.690 --> 00:53:37.240
I said this should
be the other way.

00:53:37.240 --> 00:53:38.590
That's the logic.

00:53:38.590 --> 00:53:40.120
So they laugh, like he laughed.

00:53:40.120 --> 00:53:41.286
Everybody laughed and said--

00:53:41.286 --> 00:53:42.659
[LAUGHING]

00:53:42.659 --> 00:53:44.450
JACK HIDARY: That's
the evil banking laugh.

00:53:44.450 --> 00:53:44.650
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: Absolutely.

00:53:44.650 --> 00:53:46.120
What a silly thing to ask.

00:53:46.120 --> 00:53:47.740
That's what we do.

00:53:47.740 --> 00:53:49.450
And then I hit on another point.

00:53:49.450 --> 00:53:51.994
I said, you also don't
lend money to women.

00:53:51.994 --> 00:53:53.410
Because in Bangladesh,
at the time

00:53:53.410 --> 00:53:55.420
that I was raising
this question,

00:53:55.420 --> 00:54:01.130
99% of the borrowers of all the
banks of Bangladesh are men.

00:54:01.130 --> 00:54:03.120
1% or less are the woman.

00:54:03.120 --> 00:54:05.710
So I said, you are not
only against poor people.

00:54:05.710 --> 00:54:09.830
You are also against women
because your results show that.

00:54:09.830 --> 00:54:12.260
This is not me making it up.

00:54:12.260 --> 00:54:14.330
So they said, no, no,
women don't come to us.

00:54:14.330 --> 00:54:17.540
I said, no, your rules are so
bad because when a woman comes

00:54:17.540 --> 00:54:20.000
to the proposition with
if she's a rich person,

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:23.360
she's a able person,
always manager will

00:54:23.360 --> 00:54:26.600
look at the business
proposition and then say,

00:54:26.600 --> 00:54:29.300
have you discussed
with your husband?

00:54:29.300 --> 00:54:31.040
And then he will
say, why don't you

00:54:31.040 --> 00:54:34.580
bring your husband along next
Monday so that we can discuss?

00:54:34.580 --> 00:54:36.950
I said, has it ever happened
in the history of banking

00:54:36.950 --> 00:54:40.520
in Bangladesh a man brought
his proposal to a manager

00:54:40.520 --> 00:54:43.660
and manager said, have you
discussed with your wife?

00:54:43.660 --> 00:54:45.600
Why didn't you bring
your wife with you

00:54:45.600 --> 00:54:46.880
so that we can discuss that?

00:54:46.880 --> 00:54:49.017
And I said, that's where
the discrimination begins.

00:54:49.017 --> 00:54:50.850
And that's why people
don't feel encouraged.

00:54:50.850 --> 00:54:53.850
Women don't feel-- when I
begin, I wanted to make sure

00:54:53.850 --> 00:54:57.450
I correct it because I've
been so vocal against it.

00:54:57.450 --> 00:54:59.710
So I shouldn't commit
the same mistake.

00:54:59.710 --> 00:55:02.670
So I wanted to make sure half
the borrowers in my program

00:55:02.670 --> 00:55:04.640
are women.

00:55:04.640 --> 00:55:06.260
And it was a tough job.

00:55:06.260 --> 00:55:07.890
Women say, no, no,
don't give it to me.

00:55:07.890 --> 00:55:09.670
Give it to my husband.

00:55:09.670 --> 00:55:11.230
So I don't know what to do.

00:55:11.230 --> 00:55:13.270
I keep on explaining
to my students

00:55:13.270 --> 00:55:17.019
because I'm working with the
students, who work together.

00:55:17.019 --> 00:55:19.060
They were very frustrated
working with the women.

00:55:19.060 --> 00:55:20.890
These are girl students
who were working

00:55:20.890 --> 00:55:22.810
with me to go to the women.

00:55:22.810 --> 00:55:25.000
They said, maybe we
should forget about them.

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:26.500
They said, they
don't know anything.

00:55:26.500 --> 00:55:27.970
I said, no, that's not the way.

00:55:27.970 --> 00:55:30.430
When you hear that they are
saying they cannot do anything.

00:55:30.430 --> 00:55:31.900
They are afraid of money.

00:55:31.900 --> 00:55:34.060
They don't want to create
trouble for the family.

00:55:34.060 --> 00:55:37.110
Always remember this
is the history which

00:55:37.110 --> 00:55:39.280
is making them say
that because history

00:55:39.280 --> 00:55:42.460
made them so fearful of
everything that happens new.

00:55:42.460 --> 00:55:45.130
So they want to cling
to the old things.

00:55:45.130 --> 00:55:46.730
They don't want to
expose themselves

00:55:46.730 --> 00:55:49.540
on new danger of
exposing themselves.

00:55:49.540 --> 00:55:52.300
I said, we have to peel off
the fear layer by layer.

00:55:52.300 --> 00:55:53.260
It takes time.

00:55:53.260 --> 00:55:54.740
So we go back again and again.

00:55:54.740 --> 00:55:55.870
Build confidence in them.

00:55:55.870 --> 00:55:58.210
It took us six
years in doing that.

00:55:58.210 --> 00:56:00.100
Then we came to 50-50.

00:56:00.100 --> 00:56:02.740
Then we saw something
new coming up.

00:56:02.740 --> 00:56:05.080
Money going to the
family through women

00:56:05.080 --> 00:56:07.169
brought so much more
benefit to the family

00:56:07.169 --> 00:56:09.210
than the same amount of
money going to the family

00:56:09.210 --> 00:56:10.270
through men.

00:56:10.270 --> 00:56:11.970
And you can write a
whole book on that.

00:56:11.970 --> 00:56:16.960
The kind of differences that you
see is so visible, so obvious

00:56:16.960 --> 00:56:19.390
doing that every
family have them.

00:56:19.390 --> 00:56:21.700
Then we said, why are we
having this restriction

00:56:21.700 --> 00:56:23.680
of 50% for women?

00:56:23.680 --> 00:56:25.270
Why don't you open it up?

00:56:25.270 --> 00:56:27.340
Then we opened it up
and focused on women.

00:56:27.340 --> 00:56:30.880
It slowed down our work so
much because men are just

00:56:30.880 --> 00:56:32.410
jumping around to take money.

00:56:32.410 --> 00:56:35.510
Here, women are so
reluctant, so make sure

00:56:35.510 --> 00:56:37.390
that she understands everything.

00:56:37.390 --> 00:56:39.140
So we accepted that.

00:56:39.140 --> 00:56:44.270
But gradually, it jumped up to
60%, 70%, and went beyond 90%.

00:56:44.270 --> 00:56:46.570
Then we say, let's slow
down so that we can

00:56:46.570 --> 00:56:49.610
keep some men into the picture.

00:56:49.610 --> 00:56:51.520
So we stopped in 97%.

00:56:51.520 --> 00:56:54.380
That's how we
remained 97% forever

00:56:54.380 --> 00:56:55.990
so that we don't
eliminate everything.

00:56:55.990 --> 00:56:59.200
But when it came to the USA,
they didn't bother about men,

00:56:59.200 --> 00:57:00.940
just went straight to women.

00:57:00.940 --> 00:57:02.764
And that's done
fantastically well.

00:57:02.764 --> 00:57:03.930
JACK HIDARY: Good learnings.

00:57:03.930 --> 00:57:05.140
One last question, please.

00:57:05.140 --> 00:57:06.400
But don't worry, you
guys will get books.

00:57:06.400 --> 00:57:06.720
Don't worry.

00:57:06.720 --> 00:57:07.219
Go ahead.

00:57:07.219 --> 00:57:08.005
One last question.

00:57:08.005 --> 00:57:08.230
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:57:08.230 --> 00:57:09.188
JACK HIDARY: Your name?

00:57:09.188 --> 00:57:10.369
AUDIENCE: I'm Melissa.

00:57:10.369 --> 00:57:12.160
Earlier you were
mentioning how it's really

00:57:12.160 --> 00:57:15.480
exciting that 14 million people
a year entering the workforce

00:57:15.480 --> 00:57:17.290
and how everyone should
be an entrepreneur

00:57:17.290 --> 00:57:18.609
and go into social business.

00:57:18.609 --> 00:57:20.650
But it seems to a very
small percentage of people

00:57:20.650 --> 00:57:22.233
are willing to become
an entrepreneur.

00:57:22.233 --> 00:57:24.280
And even a smaller
percentage are

00:57:24.280 --> 00:57:26.707
willing to go into
social business.

00:57:26.707 --> 00:57:29.290
What's going to have to change
to mobilize young people to get

00:57:29.290 --> 00:57:30.250
into social business?

00:57:30.250 --> 00:57:32.530
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: See, I
have always feel inspired.

00:57:32.530 --> 00:57:36.375
The previous question was what
is successful in businesses

00:57:36.375 --> 00:57:38.950
and new entrepreneurs
that are coming up.

00:57:38.950 --> 00:57:42.880
I feel encouraged what I already
explained to the young people

00:57:42.880 --> 00:57:44.110
in Bangladesh.

00:57:44.110 --> 00:57:48.190
If your illiterate mother,
who never had any experience

00:57:48.190 --> 00:57:49.810
of business of any type--

00:57:49.810 --> 00:57:51.400
she doesn't even watch TV.

00:57:51.400 --> 00:57:54.180
She doesn't know how
business is done.

00:57:54.180 --> 00:57:57.280
If she can become
entrepreneur, not one,

00:57:57.280 --> 00:58:00.220
millions of them in
Bangladesh, now probably

00:58:00.220 --> 00:58:02.170
millions of them in the US.

00:58:02.170 --> 00:58:05.320
And 300 millions
of them worldwide.

00:58:05.320 --> 00:58:08.170
I don't believe people
are not entrepreneur.

00:58:08.170 --> 00:58:10.030
I believe they are entrepreneur.

00:58:10.030 --> 00:58:13.840
Simply, our system that we build
suppressed it, locked it up,

00:58:13.840 --> 00:58:15.250
said you have to have a job.

00:58:15.250 --> 00:58:17.520
So everybody is running
around with the CV,

00:58:17.520 --> 00:58:20.770
with the recommendations,
telephone calls

00:58:20.770 --> 00:58:22.850
so that I can get a
little job with you

00:58:22.850 --> 00:58:24.420
so that my life is done.

00:58:24.420 --> 00:58:27.330
I said, that's not what the
human beings are created for.

00:58:27.330 --> 00:58:28.870
It is wrongly designed.

00:58:28.870 --> 00:58:31.540
Our mind is twisted
around to make

00:58:31.540 --> 00:58:34.870
us believe that job is the
only thing that we have to do.

00:58:34.870 --> 00:58:37.210
Our education system
is twisted around.

00:58:37.210 --> 00:58:40.180
Our family conversation
are twisted around

00:58:40.180 --> 00:58:41.770
because that's what
the theory says.

00:58:41.770 --> 00:58:43.394
You are born to work
for somebody else.

00:58:43.394 --> 00:58:45.650
I said, we are not born
to work for somebody else.

00:58:45.650 --> 00:58:46.990
I'm a free person.

00:58:46.990 --> 00:58:49.110
I do things on my own way.

00:58:49.110 --> 00:58:51.700
Unleash my own energy
on creative power.

00:58:51.700 --> 00:58:55.840
So once we establish that,
everybody will be entrepreneur.

00:58:55.840 --> 00:58:57.820
So why did all these
women become entrepreneur?

00:58:57.820 --> 00:59:01.050
Because you put the
money on the table.

00:59:01.050 --> 00:59:02.720
That's the only trick we play.

00:59:02.720 --> 00:59:04.530
When you see money
on the table, I said,

00:59:04.530 --> 00:59:05.530
why am I sitting around?

00:59:05.530 --> 00:59:06.140
There's money.

00:59:06.140 --> 00:59:07.740
I can do something.

00:59:07.740 --> 00:59:09.860
So today, that
money doesn't exist.

00:59:09.860 --> 00:59:12.440
In the schools and
colleges, you traditionally

00:59:12.440 --> 00:59:15.020
see recruiters coming
from different companies.

00:59:15.020 --> 00:59:16.460
You see that all the time.

00:59:16.460 --> 00:59:18.880
And see which of the
recruiter you can discuss,

00:59:18.880 --> 00:59:23.370
see who can get a
job in that company.

00:59:23.370 --> 00:59:25.040
No financier comes
into the campus

00:59:25.040 --> 00:59:26.930
saying that if you want
to be entrepreneur,

00:59:26.930 --> 00:59:28.670
this is what your
facility would give.

00:59:28.670 --> 00:59:29.880
This is our social venture.

00:59:29.880 --> 00:59:30.754
This is this venture.

00:59:30.754 --> 00:59:31.310
This is that.

00:59:31.310 --> 00:59:33.030
We are better than anybody else.

00:59:33.030 --> 00:59:35.060
Even if you fail,
it's OK for you.

00:59:35.060 --> 00:59:36.590
All kinds of
attractive offer there.

00:59:36.590 --> 00:59:37.790
Nobody comes.

00:59:37.790 --> 00:59:40.220
So I don't know how do
we become entrepreneur.

00:59:40.220 --> 00:59:42.410
In empty hand, you
cannot be entrepreneur.

00:59:42.410 --> 00:59:44.060
You need some
money in your hand.

00:59:44.060 --> 00:59:46.670
And the financial institution
is responsible to provide

00:59:46.670 --> 00:59:47.660
that money.

00:59:47.660 --> 00:59:51.380
I said, in order to catch a
dollar, you need a dollar.

00:59:51.380 --> 00:59:53.870
Without the first dollar, you
don't catch the next dollar.

00:59:53.870 --> 00:59:55.790
But nobody gives
that first dollar

00:59:55.790 --> 00:59:58.750
in the hands of an
unemployed young person.

00:59:58.750 --> 01:00:00.470
That's the tricky thing.

01:00:00.470 --> 01:00:03.070
You may have a most
brilliant idea of business.

01:00:03.070 --> 01:00:05.140
You go to any
bank, any investor.

01:00:05.140 --> 01:00:07.300
They will just throw you out.

01:00:07.300 --> 01:00:08.829
Who are you?

01:00:08.829 --> 01:00:09.620
That's the trouble.

01:00:09.620 --> 01:00:11.942
JACK HIDARY: Professor, it
is an honor and pleasure

01:00:11.942 --> 01:00:13.900
to have one of the true
visionaries of our time

01:00:13.900 --> 01:00:15.156
here with us today.

01:00:15.156 --> 01:00:17.030
Please let me thank
Professor Muhammad Yunus.

01:00:17.030 --> 01:00:18.113
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: Thank you.

01:00:18.113 --> 01:00:18.810
[APPLAUSE]

01:00:18.810 --> 01:00:20.350
JACK HIDARY: "World
of Three Zeros."

01:00:20.350 --> 01:00:22.300
We have some of the back
for the questioners.

01:00:22.300 --> 01:00:23.460
Thank you very much, professor.

01:00:23.460 --> 01:00:24.543
MUHAMMAD YUNUS: Thank you.

01:00:24.543 --> 01:00:25.270
Thank you.

01:00:25.270 --> 01:00:26.230
Wonderful.

01:00:26.230 --> 01:00:28.080
Thank you, too.

